node.text:
“You will be challenged during the next four years, but you can do it,” said Academy Superintendent Lt. Gen. Richard Clark. “Take one bite at a time. The first step is completing basic cadet training, and you have already demonstrated you have what it takes to succeed by getting here. I stood where you stand almost 40 years ago and I’m so glad I stuck it out.”

The global COVID-19 pandemic may be on the decline, but the Air Force Academy took no chances when more than 1,100 young men and women reported to the school for basic cadet training, June 24.

The trainees arrived between 7 a.m.-noon, were given facemasks, and immediately tested for the coronavirus.

Check out more on this story at www.usafa.edu.

node.text: Today, cadets march in a Founders Day Parade honoring the legacy of #youracademy. Together, we stand on the foundation built by those who came before us, striving to strengthen that foundation for those who come after us, reinforcing our bonds with a culture of dignity and respect. Being part of the Long Blue Line means being part of something bigger than ourselves, collectively building and bolstering the bridge to the future @usairforce  and  @spaceforcedod. The more we treat each other with dignity and respect, and ensure that this is a fundamental part of our culture, the higher we’ll rise together.

node.text:
As we honor Black History Month, I’d like to take a moment to share with you one of my favorite stories about Rosa Parks. I share this in hopes that when we think of civil rights exemplars such as Rosa Parks, the Tuskegee Airmen, Dr. Martin Luther King, and the many other pioneers of integration and racial equality, that we also reflect on ourselves. How can we better ourselves and understand that together we have an opportunity to become not only better Air and Space Forces, but a nation that champions diversity and inclusion?

#FirstieFriday Family Edition.  C1C Sean Adams comes from Illinois and both his mom and dad are graduates of #youracademy.
Sean understands the importance of balancing work and fun- making time for things like hiking and playing in a band. 
One lesson he'll remember from USAFA: "I am always learning new things about myself but probably the most important thing I've learned and will take away from the academy is that a level head and calm demeanor can solve more problems than a brilliant intellect."
Sean is an Aero major with a German minor and is a member of the club cycling team.  He hopes to serve as a pilot in the @usairforce

node.text:
The Herlik Family has provided a home-away-from-home to cadets from all over the world for more than 20 years. 

Ed Herlik (class of ’80) and his wife, Cindy Strong-Herlik, have been sponsoring cadets since 1998, and currently sponsor six cadets over three year groups. 

“We didn’t have sponsors when I was a cadet.  But, a family I met in the Chapel ‘adopted’ me, which was great! [As sponsor parents] we enjoy watching them mature and grow through the years, especially since we don’t have children,” said Herlik. “These ties also keep us a bit more connected to the Academy and the Air Force. 

Herlik served in Academy Admissions for many years, taught Political Science, and has been an ethics mentor since 1999. The cadets the Herliks have sponsored over the years have come from all over the world – roughly a third of them have been foreign exchange cadets. “When their moms spent time here on Parents’ Weekend or graduation, you can bet we happily turned the kitchen over to them for some magic!" 

"Our grads still send photos of their major milestones and bring their families by for a visit when they’re in town,” said Herlik. 

Cadet Sponsor Families are so vital to our cadet’s well-being while they are here, and to the USAFA mission at-large. They are our #USAFAfamily.

When you hear the roar of jet engines over Falcon Stadium on Saturday, it will officially be FALCON FOOTBALL SEASON! That sweet sound will be made by 4 F-16s from @lukeafb … and not only are all the pilots Academy grads, but Maj Kristopher “Swat” Holstege was also a falcon football player and is flying over a football game for the first time since graduating in 2005.

“This is a very meaningful experience for me … I vividly remember the flybys when I was a cadet and how inspiring it was to me. Additionally, one of the people who inspired me to want to become a pilot has a grandson at USAFA, and he will be at the game.”

The #USAFAfamily is in full force this weekend! #longblueline #boltbrotherhood #letsfly  @af_falcons @af_football

node.text: It's the people that make #youracademy so special.  So says this week's #FirstieFriday, C1C Sierra Lyon.  Sierra hails from Hawaii and hopes to commission into the @spaceforcedod when she graduates in May.  When not in class completing her space operations degree, she's been playing on the club water polo team, taking photos of water polo and track, or busy with duties on the cadet group and wing staff.  And whenever she's home you'll find her surfing the waves off the north shore of Oahu.  #usafa2022
